<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,970,1321]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,171,970,996]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[171,257,977,994]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">REMARKS</emphasis>
</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[257,264,970,996]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">.</emphasis>
This is the smallest of the Peruvian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1905" box="[685,808,971,996]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Majeorona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[685,808,971,996]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Majeorona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with body lengths of about 
<quantity box="[1221,1302,970,997]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" unit="mm" value="28.0">28 mm</quantity>
and a wing span of less than 
<quantity box="[351,434,1006,1033]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" unit="mm" value="80.0">80 mm</quantity>
. The head and thorax are green marked with piceous, the abdomen is piceous, the postclypeus does not extend anteriorly beyond the supra-antennal plates when viewed from the dorsal side and the lack of infuscation on the fore wing radial and radiomedial crossveins easily distinguish it from the remaining Peruvian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1905" box="[151,274,1115,1140]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Majeorona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,274,1115,1140]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Majeorona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
